ca.cgjennings.ui

Class BrowserPanel

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.awt.Component
      • java.awt.Container
        • javax.swing.JComponent
          • javax.swing.JPanel
            • ca.cgjennings.ui.BrowserPanel
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ImageObserver, MenuContainer, Serializable, Accessible

    public class BrowserPanel
extends JPanel
    A panel that contains a pluggable HTML browser. The browser can display standard URLs or can be customized to map a private address space to standard URLs and/or to generate documents on the fly. HTML rendering is provided via implementations of the BrowserPanel.ViewProvider adapter interface. The default implementation uses a JEditorPane and approximately supports HTML 3.2. An alternative provider is available that supports HTML 5 via JavaFX.
    Since:
    3.0

    Serialized Form

      • createViewProvider

        protected BrowserPanel.ViewProvider createViewProvider()
        Returns a new BrowserPanel.ViewProvider that can be used to create a component to display HTML content. The default algorithm is to try to instantiate the class named by VIEW_PROVIDER_CLASS (if it is non-null), and if that fails, to create a default view provider. This method is called during construction.
        Returns:
        the provider for this panel's content display component

      • openAddressInNewWindow

        public void openAddressInNewWindow(String address,
                                   BrowserPanel.ViewProvider requiredView)
        Subclasses may override this to support opening a link in a new window when this feature is supported by the view provider. The base class simply passes the call on to setURL(java.lang.String).

        Some view provider implementations may require that a specific view instance be used for the new window. Typically, this depends on what kind of event led to the new window request. If the view provider decides to open a location in a new window, and it requires that a specific view provider be used for the new window, then it will pass that view as the second parameter. Otherwise, the second parameter will be null. This can be used with the protected BrowserPanel(ca.cgjennings.ui.BrowserPanel.ViewProvider) constructor to create an appropriate BrowserPanel instance.

        When overriding this method, check the value of allowsNewWindowRequests() before taking any action. If it returns false, then this method should have no effect.

        Parameters:
        address - the address to open
        requiredView - the view provider to use, or null

      • setExternalBrowserEnabled

        public void setExternalBrowserEnabled(boolean enable)
        Sets whether the external browser button is available. When enabled, a small icon is shown in the address bar that allows the user to open the displayed page in their system browser (when the address is an appropriate type).
        Parameters:
        enable - true to enable the external browser button
        See Also:

      • setLoadProgress

        public void setLoadProgress(int loadProgress)
        View implementations can call this to update the progress display. Setting a value between 0 and 100 will set the current progress to that percentage value. Setting the value to -1 indicates that progress is indeterminate. Setting the value to -2 will hide the progress display. The progress bar is initially hidden.
        Parameters:
        loadProgress - the progress value to display

      • setLocationMapper

        public void setLocationMapper(BrowserPanel.LocationMapper mapper)
        Sets the location mapper. Changing the location mapper will also clear the page history, since the new mapper may not be able to correctly translate the addresses stored in the history.
        Parameters:
        mapper - the new location mapper

      • setURL

        public void setURL(String address)
        Sets the address of the displayed content. The current location mapper will be used to convert the supplied address into content; either a generated Web page or else a URL to load. (The default location mapper attempts to load the address as a URL.)
        Parameters:
        address - the address to load

      • showLinkAddress

        public void showLinkAddress(String address)
        Shows or hides the destination of a link that the mouse cursor is positioned over. This can be called by view providers when the cursor is over a link to provide feedback on the link destination. Calling this with null will clear the feedback display when the mouse cursor is moved off of the link.
        Parameters:
        address - the address to display, or null
